The '''Yugoslav coup d'<U+00E9>tat''' occurred on 27 March 1941 in [[Belgrade]], [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia]]. The coup was planned and conducted by a group of pro-Western [[Serbs|Serb]]-nationalist [[Royal Yugoslav Air Force]] officers formally led by Air Force General [[Du<U+0161>an Simovi<U+0107>]], who had been associated with a number of coup plots from 1938 onwards. For practical purposes Brigadier General of Military Aviation [[Borivoje Mirkovi<U+0107>]], Major [[<U+017D>ivan Kne<U+017E>evi<U+0107>]] of the Yugoslav [[Royal Guard]]s, and his brother [[Radoje Kne<U+017E>evi<U+0107>]] all performed leadership roles in the conduct of the coup. In addition to Radoje Kne<U+017E>evi<U+0107>, some other civilian leaders were probably aware of the coup before it was launched and moved to support it once it occurred, but they were not among the organisers. The [[League of Communists of Yugoslavia|Communist Party of Yugoslavia]] played no part in the coup, although it made a significant contribution to the mass street protests in many cities that signalled popular support for the coup after it occurred. The coup was successful and overthrew the three-member regency: [[Prince Paul of Yugoslavia|Prince Paul]], Dr. [[Radenko Stankovi<U+0107>]] and Dr. [[Ivo Perovi<U+0107>]], as well as the government of Prime Minister [[Dragi<U+0161>a Cvetkovi<U+0107>]]. Two days before the coup, the Cvetkovi<U+0107> government had signed the [[Vienna]] Protocol on the Accession of Yugoslavia to the [[Tripartite Pact]] (Axis). The coup had been planned for several months, but the signing of the Tripartite Pact spurred the organisers to carry it out, encouraged by the British [[Special Operations Executive]]. 
 
The military conspirators brought to power the 17-year-old King [[Peter II of Yugoslavia|Peter II Kara<U+0111>or<U+0111>evi<U+0107>]], who they declared to be of age to assume the throne, and a government of national unity was formed with Simovi<U+0107> as prime minister and [[Vladko Ma<U+010D>ek]] and [[Slobodan Jovanovi<U+0107>]] as his vice-premiers. The coup resulted in the [[Nazi Germany|German]]-led [[Axis powers|Axis]] [[invasion of Yugoslavia]].

==Background==

From the moment of its creation, the [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia]] was politically weak and remained so during the [[interwar period]] mainly due to a "rigid system of centralism",{{sfn|Tomasevich|1969|p=60}} the strong association between each national group and its dominant religion,{{sfn|Tomasevich|1969|pp=61<U+2013>62}} and uneven economic development.{{sfn|Tomasevich|1969|p=62}} In particular, the religious primacy of the [[Serbian Orthodox Church]] in national affairs and discrimination against [[Roman Catholic]]s and [[Muslim]]s compounded the dissatisfaction of the non-[[Serbs|Serb]] population with the Serb-dominated ruling groups that treated non-Serbs as second-class citizens.{{sfn|Tomasevich|1969|pp=61<U+2013>62}} This centralised system was created through political bribery and until 1929 it was maintained by subverting the democratic system of government. The domination of the rest of Yugoslavia by Serb ruling elites meant that the country was never consolidated in the political sense, and was therefore never able to address the social and economic challenges it faced.{{sfn|Tomasevich|1969|p=61}} According to the political scientist Professor Sabrina Ramet, the dysfunctionality and lack of legitimacy of the regime meant that politics became ethnically polarised, a phenomena that has been referred to as the "national question" in Yugoslavia. Failures to establish the rule of law, to protect individual rights, to build tolerance and equality, and to guarantee the neutrality of the state in matters relating to religion, language and culture contributed to this illegitimacy and the resulting instability.{{sfn|Ramet|2006|p=76}} In 1929 democracy was abandoned and a [[6 January Dictatorship|royal dictatorship]] was established by [[Alexander I of Yugoslavia|King Alexander]],{{sfn|Tomasevich|1969|p=61}} who attempted to breakdown the ethnic divisions in the country through a number of means, including creating administrative divisions ({{lang-sh|banovina}}) based on rivers rather than traditional regions.{{sfn|Ramet|2006|pp=79<U+2013>80}} There was significant opposition to this move, with Serb and Slovenian opposition parties and figures advocating the division of Yugoslavia into six ethnically-based  administrative units. By 1933, discontent in the [[Sava Banovina]] had developed into full-blown civil disorder, which the regime countered with a series of assassinations, attempted assassinations and arrests of key Croatian opposition figures including the leader of the [[Croatian Peasant Party]] (Hrvatska selja<U+010D>ka stranka, HSS) [[Vladko Ma<U+010D>ek]].{{sfn|Ramet|2006|p=87}} When Alexander was assassinated in Marseilles in 1934, his cousin [[Prince Paul of Yugoslavia|Prince Paul]] headed a [[triumvirate]] [[Regency (government)|regency]] whose other members were the senator Dr. [[Radenko Stankovi<U+0107>]] and the governor of the Sava Banovina, Dr. Ivo Perovi<U+0107>. The regency ruled on behalf of Alexander's 11 year old son, [[Peter II of Yugoslavia|Prince Peter]], but the important member of the regency was Prince Paul.{{sfn|Dragnich|1983|p=99}} Although Prince Paul was more liberal than his cousin, the dictatorship continued uninterrupted.{{sfn|Tomasevich|1969|pp=60<U+2013>63}}

===Cvetkovi<U+0107><U+2013>Ma<U+010D>ek Agreement===

