===Axis invasion===
{{main|Invasion of Yugoslavia}}
The Axis invasion of Yugoslavia began on 6 April. The [[Bombing of Belgrade in World War II|bombing of Belgrade]] forced the government to seek shelter outside the city.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=50}} From here, King Peter and General Simovi<U+0107> planned to leave for exile. Ma<U+010D>ek, refusing to leave the country, resigned on 7 April and designated [[Juraj Krnjevi<U+0107>]] as his successor.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=50}} Ma<U+010D>ek returned to Zagreb. Three other ministers also refused to leave Yugoslavia: [[Ivan Andres]] and [[Bari<U+0161>a Smoljan]] of the HSS and Kulenovi<U+0107> of the JMO.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=50}} The government met on Yugoslav soil for the last time on 13 April near [[Pale, Bosnia and Herzegovina|Pale]]. From here they travelled to [[Nik<U+0161>i<U+0107>]] where they were flown out of the country to Athens.{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2007|p=19}} 

Another result of the coup was that the work that had been done by British intelligence with the anti-Axis government of Cvetkovi<U+0107> and Ma<U+010D>ek was lost. By supporting the coup plotters, SOE Belgrade undermined the balance in Yugoslav politics that had been achieved by the Cvetkovi<U+0107><U+2013>Ma<U+010D>ek Agreement. Serb nationalists supported and welcomed the coup because it ended Croatian autonomy under the Agreement and freed them to pursue a [[Greater Serbia]] agenda.{{sfn|Stari<U+010D>|2005|p=38}}

===Legacy===
Prince Paul was found guilty of war crimes in September 1945 for his role in the acceptance of the Tripartite Pact. In 2011, a High Court in Serbia found the sentence to be politically and ideologically motivated and Prince Paul was officially rehabilitated.{{sfn|''AFP''|6 October 2012}}{{sfn|''RTS''|15 December 2011}} A similar decision was made in 2009 which rehabilitated Cvetkovi<U+0107> for war crimes charges relating to the signing of the pact.{{sfn|''Politika''|26 September 2009}}

